  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. These aren't laws directly enforceable in individual countries, but rather agreements that encourage and often require signatory nations to enact their own national laws to address the issue.  Here are some key international frameworks:\n\n*   **The Vienna Convention (1988):** Formally known as the United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances. This convention was one of the first major international efforts to address money laundering, specifically related to drug trafficking. It requires countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug-related crimes.\n\n*   **The Palermo Convention (2000):** Also known as the United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime. This convention expands the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug trafficking to include the proceeds of other serious crimes, such as human trafficking, arms dealing, and corruption.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** While not a treaty, the FATF is an inter-governmental body that sets international standards to combat money laundering, terrorist financing, and proliferation financing. Its 40 Recommendations are recognized as the global standard and are widely adopted by countries worldwide. Countries are assessed on their compliance with these recommendations.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990) and Revised Convention (2005):** These conventions focus on the prevention and control of money laundering, and on the search, seizure, and confiscation of the proceeds of crime. They promote international cooperation in these areas.\n\n*   **European Union Directives:** The European Union has issued several directives on money laundering that member states are required to implement into their national laws. These directives set standards for customer due diligence, reporting suspicious transactions, and beneficial ownership transparency.\n\n**Key elements addressed by these laws and frameworks include:**\n\n*   **Criminalization:** Requiring countries to criminalize money laundering as a separate offense.\n*   **Customer Due Diligence (CDD):**  Requiring financial institutions and other designated businesses to identify and verify the identities of their customers.\n*   **Record Keeping:**  Requiring financial institutions to maintain records of transactions for a certain period of time.\n*   **Reporting Suspicious Transactions:** Requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions to the relevant authorities (often Financial Intelligence Units or FIUs).\n*   **International Cooperation:**  Promoting cooperation among countries in investigating and prosecuting money laundering offenses, including sharing information and providing mutual legal assistance.\n*   **Confiscation of Assets:**  Enabling the confiscation of assets derived from or involved in money laundering.\n*   **Beneficial Ownership Transparency:** Requiring disclosure of the true owners of legal entities to prevent the use of shell companies for money laundering.\n\n**In summary:** While there isn't a single, universally applicable \"international law\" against money laundering, there is a robust framework of international conventions, standards, and agreements that encourage and often mandate countries to enact their own national laws to combat money laundering. These frameworks promote international cooperation and the adoption of common standards, making it more difficult for criminals to launder the proceeds of their illicit activities across borders.\n",
